main event: A professional photographer in Boston, Massachusetts submitted photographs of unusual objects in the sky over Boston Harbor in 1956.
interesting points: The objects were described as circular, silver in color, and approximately 40-50 feet in diameter.
The objects were moving slowly and silently across the sky in a north-to-south direction.
The photographer was hesitant to submit the photographs earlier due to fear of ridicule.
MIT Lincoln Laboratories, which employed the photographer, had access to advanced photographic analysis equipment.
The Air Force Cambridge Research Center requested the Air Technical Intelligence Center to analyze the negatives and provide feedback on what was shown in the film.
sighted object: Circular, silver objects in the sky
witnesses: Professional photographer employed by MIT Lincoln Laboratories
photographs: Yes, the report includes photographs that were submitted to the Air Force
